text:
Can we please stop sharing this Salary benchmark survey sheet!
1. I have experience doing 200+ candidate discovery calls and I can dispute atleast 50% of the data.
2. It has poor data integrity (there are negative values in it!).
3. And there is no visibility on how representative is this survey, how many participants took this survey or which cohorts are either over-represented or under-represented. 
It’s a good attempt but the outcome is just poor and misleading.

text:
Absolutely agreed on the cohort representation. That's why we want as many people to take it to nullify any outliers that have been mis/under/over represented

The more ppl take this survey, the better the output. 

Regarding data - would be happy to chat 1-1 but a lot of folks who have taken interviews see this as a decent approximation. Can it be overindexing or underindexing? Maybe - markets and wages in SaaS startups move fast. A Demand Gen expert with 4-5 years of exp in SaaS can make a leadership jump and move from late 20's/early 30's to 50's while folks who have been on the lower scale for sometime might not see their correction. 
Happy to discuss 1-1 more on this and if you are open (and the form fills are anon) would like you to work with us on the report :slightly_smiling_face:

text:
Can we please stop sharing value in this community!

1. I have experience outside this community that is AWESOME and this community doesn’t count in front of that!
2. Why should I be grateful for people here who are filling their survey to help each other. (there are some errors in the data!) It was conducted by Gallop, and not an open community trying their best to educate and help each other.
3. And there is no visibility on who is filling the survey so that I can shit post and get insecure when I see someone with lesser experience getting paid more than me

It’s a good attempt but the outcome is just poor and misleading me to make more errors and continue setting the salary bar and expectations really low in our market.

text: Friday thoughts. Is it worthwhile to pursue and scale startups (while sacrificing a lot of personal, family and fun time) or quietly live a 9 to 5 while earning 30% lesser but having enough time on hand. I know disproportionate wealth creation is a valid argument but thats hardly for . 01% or . 001% of orgs. In the end does it matter?

I know disproportionate wealth creation is a valid argument but thats hardly for . 01% or . 001% of orgs. In the end does it matter?

text:
Depends on multiple aspects:

1. If you are getting any stock options, now a days most startups provide that, after a good amount of time spent for the startup those do hold value. 
2. What's your personal goal and your plan for it?
3. If you are already self-actualised, mentoring and relaxing might be the right answer.

text:
It doesn’t matter actually!

It doesn’t matter if you’re slogging away building a company, creating wealth — but loosing the limited time we all get (in this life) to spend with our parents/spouse/children/friends/pets.

Equally, it doesn’t matter if you take up a very humble job and spend the time you get with your family/friends/pet or even a non-paying passion/hobby.

And both these choices have diminishing returns (eventually).

So, what matters is which choice you’d regret (more!)?
